Space=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#eeb3b3;strokeColor=#c0392b;fontColor=#5a1410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="1358" y="1093" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+3+4+5+7+8+9+10]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   198k lives-eq/$1k · 61% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 39%&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + nature_intrinsic_value + climate_tipping_points + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + animals_matter_a_lot + suffering_focused + meat_eater_problem + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 3 nature_intrinsic_value → 4 climate_tipping_points → 5 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 suffering_focused → 9 meat_eater_problem → 10 net_negative_animal_lives" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJytWWtv2zgW%2FSsXwXbXTv2Q5He6WSDNY1o0aYM03WDQFCot0TY3Eqklpbhup%2F3te0lKspw4Ew28HxqoknjuuU8e0T%2F2QjojWZQei5DuHex1u3B4eAjXkjAOqYBAku8rvFhyuM08x%2B3DUsgovGd0CUvX9%2Fye3%2FcH%2Fsgf%2BxPfdaChUpGA6zQ1zC1HuCOlsjhJmeAQLBD1ABxIiBTBgpFI